	imes b_2]=\{x\}	imes [0,b_2) \subset (a_1	imes b_1, a_2 	imes b_2)\] Note that \((x	imes -1,x	imes b_2)\cap I^2\) is a basis element of subspace topology. Case IV \((a_1=x=a_2)\): \[x	imes y \in (x	imes b_1,x	imes b_2)\cap I^2= [x	imes b_1,x	imes b_2]=\{x\}	imes [b_1,b_2) \subset (a_1	imes b_1, a_2 	imes b_2)\] Note that \((x	imes b_1,x	imes b_2)\cap I^2\) is a basis element of subspace topology. See figure 4.3 In above all four cases, we have found basis element of subspace topology that contain \(x	imes y\) and contained in \((a_1	imes b_1, a_2 	imes b_2)\). Therefore, \(\mathcal{T_2}\subsetneq\mathcal{T3}\) Figure 4.3: \(~\) 4.3 Section 17 in Munkress Book Exercise 4.17 (Mun 2.17.1) Let \(\mathcal{C}\) be a collection of subsets of the set \(X\). Suppose that $$and \(X\) are in \(\mathcal{C}\), and that finite unions and arbitrary intersections of elements of \(\mathcal{C}\) are in \(\mathcal{C}\). Show that the collection \[\mathcal{T} = \{X \setminus C | C\in \mathcal{C}\}\] is a topology on X. Solution: Proof. (T1) \(\emptyset \in \mathcal{C}\implies X\setminus \emptyset=X \in \mathcal{T}\). \(X \in \mathcal{C}\implies X\setminus X=\emptyset \in \mathcal{T}\) (T2) Let \(\{U_\alpha\}_{\alpha\in J}\) be family of elements in \(\mathcal{C}\). Then \((X\setminus U_\alpha\}_{\alpha\in J}\in \mathcal{T}\). Then, \[ igcup_{\alpha\in J}(X\setminus U_\alpha)=X\setminus  igcup_{\alpha\in J}U_\alpha\] Since \(\mathcal{C}\) is closed arbitrary intersection, \( igcup_{\alpha\in J}\in \mathcal{C}\). Thus,\( igcap_{\alpha\in J}(X\setminus U_\alpha)=X\setminus  igcup_{\alpha\in J}U_\alpha\in \mathcal{T}\). (T3) Let \(U_1,U_2,...,U_n\in \mathcal{C}\). Then \((X\setminus U_1),(X\setminus U_2),...,(X\setminus U_n)\in \mathcal{T}\). Then, \[ igcap_{i=1}^n(X\setminus U_i)=X\setminus  igcup_{i=1}^nU_i\] Since \(\mathcal{C}\) is closed under finite union, \( igcup_{i=1}^nU_i\in \mathcal{C}\). Thus,\( igcap_{i=1}^n(X\setminus U_i)=X\setminus  igcup_{i=1}^nU_i\in \mathcal{T}\). Therefore \(\mathcal{T}\) is a topology on \(X\). Exercise 4.18 (Mun 2.17.2) Show that if \(A\) is closed in \(Y\) and \(Y\) is closed in \(X\), then \(A\) is closed in \(X\). Proof. Since \(Y\) is subspace in \(X\) and \(A\) is closed in \(Y\), by theorm 1.3, then there exist closed set \(C\) in \(X\) such that \[A=Y\cap C\] Since, \(Y\) is closed in \(X\) and \(X\) is toplogical space, \(A=Y\cap C\) is closed in \(X\). Exercise 4.19 (Mun 2.17.3) Show that if \(A\) is closed in \(X\) and \(B\) is closed in \(Y\) , then \(A	imes B\) is closed in \(X	imes Y\) Proof. Suppose that \(A\) is closed in \(X\) and \(B\) is closed in \(Y\). Then \(X\setminus A\) is open in \(X\) and \(X\setminus B\) is open in \(Y\). Claim: \((X	imes Y) \setminus (A	imes B)= ((X\setminus A)	imes Y)\cup((X	imes (Y\setminus B)))\) Proof of Claim: \[ egin{eqnarray} (x	imes y)\in (X	imes Y) \setminus (A	imes B) &amp;\iff &amp; (x	imes y)
